'''Kim Hyong-gwon''' ({{korean|hangul = 김형권}}; 4 November 1905 – 12 January 1936) was a Korean revolutionary. He is known for attacking a Japanese police station in [[Japanese-occupied Korea]] and subsequently dying in Seoul's [[Seodaemun Prison]] where he was serving his sentence.

Kim Hyong-gwon was an uncle of the founding [[North Korean leader]], [[Kim Il-sung]].{{sfn|An Indomitable Revolutionary Fighter&nbsp;— Comrade Kim Hyong Gwon|1976|p=[5]}} As such, he is among the most celebrated of the [[Kim dynasty (North Korea)|Kim family]] members in [[North Korean propaganda]]. [[Kimhyonggwon County]] in [[North Korea]] is named after him.

==Personal life==
[[File:Seodaemunprisonbarracks.jpg|thumb|alt=The barracks of Seodaemun Prison during winter.|Seodaemun Prison, where Kim Hyong-gwon died, was used for keeping anti-colonial activists in custody.]]
In his youth, Kim Hyong-gwon studied in Sunhwa school near his home in present-day [[Mangyongdae]], [[Pyongyang]].{{sfn|An Indomitable Revolutionary Fighter&nbsp;— Comrade Kim Hyong Gwon|1976|p=[7]}}

Kim was a revolutionary fighter and an active communist in the 1930s. His personality has been described as "hot-tempered".<ref name="Martin2007">{{cite book|author=Bradley K. Martin|title=Under the Loving Care of the Fatherly Leader: North Korea and the Kim Dynasty|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qoZx6hOCNukC|date=1 April 2007|publisher=St. Martin's Press|page=191 |isbn=978-1-4299-0699-9}}</ref> In August 1930, he led a small detachment of guerrillas across the [[Amnok]] (Yalu) river to [[Japanese-occupied Korea]] from Manchuria.{{sfn|An Indomitable Revolutionary Fighter&nbsp;— Comrade Kim Hyong Gwon|1976|p=[5]}} His small group's actions near Pungsan at that time got noticed by the Japanese press.{{sfn|An Indomitable Revolutionary Fighter&nbsp;— Comrade Kim Hyong Gwon|1976|p=[14]}} He captured two Japanese police cars, and both of these acts occurred in mountainous terrain.{{sfn|An Indomitable Revolutionary Fighter&nbsp;— Comrade Kim Hyong Gwon|1976|p=[12]}}{{sfn|An Indomitable Revolutionary Fighter&nbsp;— Comrade Kim Hyong Gwon|1976|pp=[18–19]}} Some time after attacking a Japanese police station in [[Kimhyonggwon County|Pungsan]], he was arrested near [[Hongwon]].{{sfn|An Indomitable Revolutionary Fighter&nbsp;— Comrade Kim Hyong Gwon|1976|p=[12]}} He was sentenced to 15 years in prison when he was 28 years old. He died on 12 January 1936, during his sentence in [[Seoul]]'s [[Seodaemun Prison]],{{sfn|An Indomitable Revolutionary Fighter&nbsp;— Comrade Kim Hyong Gwon|1976|p=[5], [29]}}<ref name="Cathcart2012">{{cite web |url=http://sinonk.com/2012/01/14/historical-allegorie-revolutionary-credentials/ |title=Historical Allegories and Revolutionary Credentials: Jang Song Taek |last=Cathcart |first=Adam |date=14 January 2012 |website=[[Sino-NK]] |publisher= |access-date=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref name="KoreanHistory">{{cite web |url=http://koreanhistory.info/KimIlSungsLife.htm |title=Kim Il Sung's Life to the Korean War |author= |date= |website=KoreanHistory.info |publisher= |access-date=11 July 2015}}</ref> where [[Korean independence movement|anti-Japanese dissidents]] were detained from 1910 to 1945 in cruel conditions.<ref name="LonelyPlanet">{{cite web |url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/south-korea/seoul/sights/museums-galleries/seodaemun-prison |title=Seodaemun Prison |author= |date= |website=[[Lonely Planet]] |publisher= |access-date=11 July 2015}}</ref>

Kim Il-sung remarks in his autobiography ''[[With the Century]]'', that it was a corrupt yet close Manchurian local official, Chae Jin Yong, who betrayed his uncle and became an informer against him.<ref name="Cathcart2012"/>

==Legacy==
[[File:Revolutionary Martyrs Cemetery 21.JPG|thumb|Bust at the [[Revolutionary Martyrs' Cemetery]]]]
Kim Hyong-gwon is among the most important Kim family members in propaganda, and comparable in that context to other prominent family members like Kim Il-sung's father [[Kim Hyong-jik]], or great grandfather Kim Ung-u, who is claimed to have been involved in the [[General Sherman incident]].<ref name="Lim2015">{{cite book|author=Jae-Cheon Lim|title=Leader Symbols and Personality Cult in North Korea: The Leader State|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pcwqBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT68|date=24 March 2015|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-56740-0}}</ref><ref name="Whyte2014">{{cite web|url=http://smallcrowdedworld.com/2014/03/21/anti-americanism-in-korea-why-one-of-our-closest-allies-has-mixed-feelings/ |title=Anti-Americanism in South Korea: Why one of our closest allies has mixed feelings |last=Whyte |first=Leon |date=21 March 2014 |website=smallcrowdedworld.com |publisher= |access-date=11 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713232825/http://smallcrowdedworld.com/2014/03/21/anti-americanism-in-korea-why-one-of-our-closest-allies-has-mixed-feelings/ |archivedate=13 July 2015 |df= }}</ref> North Korean propaganda insists that most family members were in some way participating in the foundation of the North Korean state and among them Kim Hyong-gwon is portrayed as having been sacrificed for [[anti-Japanese struggle]] and the revolution.<ref name="Lim2015"/>

Kim Hyong-gwon was included into [[North Korea's cult of personality|the personality cult]] in 1976.<ref name="Lim2010">{{cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jae_Cheon_Lim/publication/233071677_Institutionalization_of_the_cult_of_the_Kims_its_implications_for_North_Korean_political_succession/links/54d18ba00cf25ba0f0416390.pdf |title=Institutionalization of the cult of the Kims: its implications for North Korean political succession |author=Jae-Cheon Lim |date=September 2010 |website=[[ResearchGate]] |publisher= |access-date=11 July 2015}} [[North Korean media]] uses similar honorifics for him as they use with Kim Il-sung, [[Kim Jong-il]], [[Kim Jong-un]] and [[Kim Jong-suk]].</ref> [[North Korean media]] uses similar honorifics for him as they use with Kim Il-sung, [[Kim Jong-il]], [[Kim Jong-un]] and [[Kim Jong-suk]].<ref name="Donga2010">{{cite web |url=http://english.donga.com/srv/service.php3?biid=2010110522988 |title=NK Media Using Honorific Language on Heir Apparent |author= |date=5 November 2010 |website=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]] |publisher= |access-date=11 July 2015}}</ref>

[[Kimhyonggwon County]], previously known as Pungsan, in southeastern [[Ryanggang Province]], was renamed after him in August 1990.<ref name="Seoul2002">{{cite book|author=Yonhap News Agency, Seoul|title=North Korea Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JIlh9nNeadMC|date=27 December 2002|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-3523-5|page=47}}</ref> There is also a [[Kim Hyong Gwon Teachers' College]] named after him, and Hamnam University of Education Nr. 1 was renamed [[Kim Hyong Gwon University of Education]] in 1990. Both of them are in [[Sinpo]].<ref name="Dormels2014">{{cite web |url=http://www.univie.ac.at/koreanologie/fileadmin/user_upload/DigitalNK/Forschungsarbeit/Sinpho.pdf |title=Profiles of the cities of DPR Korea&nbsp;– Sinpho |last=Dormels |first=Rainer |date=2014 |website=[[University of Vienna]] |publisher= |format=PDF |access-date=11 July 2015}}</ref> Various sites of honor and statues have been made in Kim's memory. Once every five years, a ceremony is held on the days of his death and birth.<ref name="Lim2015"/>

A [[List of North Korean films|North Korean film]] ''[[A Fire Burning All Over the World]]'' was made in 1977, and it deals with both [[Kang Pan-sok]] and Kim Hyong-gwon's revolutionary deeds. The film was also the first one to portray Il-sung.<ref name="Lim2015"/>

