'''Marlon Dewitt Green'''<ref name=turbulence>{{cite book|title=Turbulence Before Takeoff: The Life & Times of Aviation Pioneer Marlon Dewitt Green|first=Flint | last=Whitlock |publisher=Cable Publishing|year=2009|isbn=978-1-934980-66-8}}</ref> (June 6, 1929 &ndash; July 6, 2009) was an [[African-American]] pilot whose landmark [[United States Supreme Court]] decision in 1963 helped dismantle [[racial discrimination]] in the [[United States|American]] passenger airline industry, leading to David Harris' hiring as the first African-American pilot for a major airline the following year. Green was subsequently hired by [[Continental Airlines]], for whom he flew from 1965 to 1978.
==Biography==
Marlon Green was born in [[El Dorado, Arkansas|El Dorado]], [[Arkansas]]. His father, Mickinley Green, was born in 1900,{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}} and married Green's future mother, Lucy, on April 10, 1921.{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}} Green's brother Rudolph Valentino Green was born in 1928, followed by Marlon (June 6, 1929); Jean Evelyn (1933); James Zell (1936); and Allen David (1941).{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}
In 1936 or 1937, the family moved to [[Lansing, Michigan|Lansing]], [[Michigan]], where he found work at the Drop Forge Company. He later joined the household staff of dentist J. Shelton Rushing as what his son called the [[major domo]].<ref name=turbulence-2>Whitlock {{page needed|date=May 2013}}</ref>
Marlon Green joined the [[United States Air Force]], where his last posting was flying the [[SA-16 Albatross]] with the [[36th Air Rescue Squadron]] at [[Johnson Air Base]] in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]].<ref name=avstop>{{cite web|url= http://www.avstop.com/history/blackairlines/marlongreen.htm |title=Black Airline Pilots: Marlon Green |publisher=AvStop.com / Aviation Online}}</ref> While on leave in 1957, he applied for a pilot position with [[Continental Airlines]], and was invited to be interviewed after having left blank the racial-identity question on the application.<ref name=avstop /> He also omitted pasting into the small square block provided in the upper right hand corner of the first page of the application, a picture of himself, Five other white applicants, less qualified, were hired. Per varying sources, he either was rejected then,<ref name=avstop /> or was hired as what would have been the nation's first African-American pilot for a major commercial airline, but was rejected after reporting for orientation.<ref name=tulsa>{{cite news|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/business/article.aspx?articleID=20080228_5_E3_spanc46213 | title=AA Honors First Black Airline Pilot | first= D. R. | last= Stewart | work=[[Tulsa World]]|location = [[Oklahoma]]|date=February 28, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111220000000/http://www.tulsaworld.com/business/article.aspx?articleID=20080228_5_E3_spanc46213 | archivedate=December 20, 2011| deadurl=no|quote=Marlon Green would have been the nation's first African-American commercial pilot, but 10 airlines rejected his application in 1957 after a nine-year Air Force career. Accepted by [[Continental Airlines]], Green showed up for orientation classes and was promptly rejected. It took a unanimous decision by the U.S. Supreme Court in 1963 to force Continental to reinstate Green, who flew for the airline from 1965 to 1978.}}</ref> On April 22, 1963, following oral arguments on March 28, 1963, the [[United States Supreme Court]] ruled in "Colorado Anti-Discrimination Commission v. Continental Airlines, Inc. 372 U.S. 714 no. 146" that Green had been unlawfully discriminated against.<ref name=supremecourt>{{Cite court | vol = 372 | pinpoint = 714 | reporter = U.S. | court = Supreme Court | litigants = Colorado Anti-Discrimination Comm'n v. Continental Air Lines, Inc. | date = 1963-04-22 | url = https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=2245319904809963785 | accessdate = 2013-05-27 }}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Per the court decision, Green had not been formally hired: "His application was submitted at Continental's headquarters in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], and was later considered and rejected there."<ref name=supremecourt />|group="Note"|name="hired"}} In 1964, [[American Airlines]] hired David Harris as the first African-American pilot for major US passenger airline.<ref name=tulsa /> Following his Supreme Court victory, Green flew for Continental from 1965 to 1978, initially piloting [[Vickers Viscount]]s out of Denver.<ref name=avstop /> He became a captain in 1966.{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}
Green died aged 80 in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]]. He was divorced and is survived by his three daughters and three sons.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Virginia Culver | title = Pilot Marlon D. Green fought racial discrimination | work = The Denver Post | location = Denver, Colo. | accessdate = 2013-05-28 | date = 2009-07-10 | url = http://www.denverpost.com/obituaries/ci_12805244 }}</ref> On February 16,<!--not Feb. 9 as some secondhand sources say; the reliable-source Houston Chronicle newspaper article is dated Friday, Feb. 19, 2010, and it says the ceremony occurred Tuesday [Feb. 16]--> 2010,<ref name=houston /> at [[George Bush Intercontinental Airport]] in [[Houston]], [[Texas]],<ref name=avstop /> Continental Airlines named a [[Boeing 737|Boeing 737-824]] (N77518, cn 31605)>{{#tag:ref|{{cite web|url=http://www.opshots.net/gallery2/index.php?page=photos&id=20604|title=Aviation Gallery|first=Chuck, Jr., ed.|last =Slusarczyk|publisher=OPShots.net|date=April 30, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723233241/http://www.opshots.net/gallery2/index.php?page=photos&id=20604|archivedate=July 23, 2011|deadurl=no}}<ref group=lower-alpha>Archived version does not include photo of the aircraft</ref>|name=""}} after him.<ref name=houston>{{cite news|last=Buggs|first=Shannon|url= http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/business/6859688.html |title=Milestone in Diversity / Continental Airlines names jetliner after trailblazing pilot|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=February 19, 2010|accessdate=February 9, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604063353/http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/business/6859688.html|archivedate=June 4, 2011|deadurl=no}}</ref>
During his lifetime, Green was inducted into the Arkansas Aviation Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newhopeflighttrainingacademy.com/MarlonGreen.cfm |title=Honoring an icon|publisher= New Hope Flight Training Academy|location=[[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Florida]]|date=n.d.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928192102/http://www.newhopeflighttrainingacademy.com/MarlonGreen.cfm|archivedate=September 28, 2007}}</ref>
