'''Roman Evsey Glazman''' (June 26, 1948 – April 24, 2006) was a [[Russian American]] [[physicist]] and [[oceanographer]].

==Early life and education==
Roman E. Glazman was born in [[St. Petersburg]], Russia, on June 26, 1948<ref name=obit>{{cite web|url=http://scitation.aip.org/content/aip/magazine/physicstoday/news/10.1063/PT.4.2329|title=Roman Glazman|work=Physics Today|date=April 2006|accessdate=January 17, 2016}}</ref> in a secular Jewish family.  He became a [[citizen]] of the United States on October 28, 1985 and completed his PhD in Ocean Engineering at the [[University Of Rhode Island]] in 1985.{{cn|date=October 2017}}

==Career==
Glazman's scientific research was the study of ocean and atmosphere. He began working at [[NASA]]'s [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] in La Cañada Flintridge and Pasadena, California.

Glazman published more than 40 works in Oceanography<ref>{{cite web | title= Library of Oceanography | url=http://www.libraryofOceanography.com }} works by Roman E. Glazman and co-authors at Library of Oceanography</ref> in scientific journals and completed over 60 research studies presenting at International Scientific Conferences, including OCEANS Conference<ref>{{cite web|title=Experiments on Sea Level Measurements Using S-Band Interferometric Techniques, 1981|author=Roman E. Glazman|url=http://www.romanglazman.com/papers.php?myYear=1981&pgnum=1}}</ref>, Geoscience and Remote Sensing International Symposium ([[IEEE Geoscience and Remote Sensing Society|IGARSS]]), [[Compromise of 1877|Wormley Conference]], [[American Geophysical Union|American Geophysical Union Conference]] (AGU)<ref>{{cite web|title=Long Internal Gravity Waves as a Factor Of Large Scale Transport|url=http://abstractsearch.agu.org/meetings/2002/OS/OS51D-10.html}}</ref>,  International Association for Physical Sciences of the Ocean, [[International Union of Geodesy and Geophysics]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Fluctuations of SST and CHL-A Concentration Caused by Baroclinic Inertia-Gravity Waves|url=http://www.iugg.org/assemblies/1999birmingham/1999abstracts.pdf}}</ref>.

Glazman conducted exploratory expeditions in the [[Bering Sea]] and the [[North Pacific Ocean]] off the coast of [[Kamchatka]] and [[Japan]], the [[Arctic]], as well as the [[Barents Sea]] off the coast of [[Finland]].  He took measurements of the depths and [[salinity]] of oceans, of the wind forces, pressures and surface temperatures, by experimentation equipped with vessel technology available in the 1970s.{{cn|date=October 2017}}

The topics in which Glazman made contributions include wave dynamics,<ref>{{cite web|title=Equatorial Wave Regime Rossby Solitons|url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/search.jsp?R=20060031290&hterms=Equatorial+wave+regime+Rossby+solitons&qs=N%3D0%26Ntk%3DAll%26Ntt%3DEquatorial%2520wave%2520regime%2520and%2520Rossby%2520solitons%26Ntx%3Dmode%2520matchall.}}</ref> capillary- and inertia-gravity waves,<ref>{{cite web|title=A Simple Theory of Capillary-Gravity Wave Turbulence|url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19970009859.pdf}}</ref> nonlinear waves and turbulence, [[Rossby wave]]s, [[sea level]] measurements, sea surface geometry, [[magnetic field]] at sea surface, wind generated wave dynamics,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Effect of the Degree Of Wave Development On The Sea State Bias in Radar Altimetry Measurement|url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/search.jsp?N=0&Ntk=Title&Ntt=The%20effect%20of%20the%20degree%20of%20wave%20development%20on%20the%20sea&Ntx=mode%20matchall}}</ref> adsorbed film and oscillations.

